Great question â€” this is the exact pressure point in the whole construction.

Short answer up front, then weâ€™ll walk it:

Aliceâ€™s first token does not receive infinite dividends because each new penny is split across an ever-growing number of tokens. The dilution grows faster than time.

Now letâ€™s say that slowly, in human language, without symbols until the end.

Restate the rules (important)
No fixed supply

A token is created at the moment of sale

Each press:

costs 1 penny

creates 1 new token

distributes that penny equally to all existing tokens (including the new one in n+0)

So:

1 press â†’ 1 token â†’ 1 penny distributed

Tokens accumulate forever

Alice can hold tokens forever

So the naive intuition is:

â€œIf presses keep happening forever, why doesnâ€™t Aliceâ€™s first token receive infinite money?â€

That intuition is reasonable â€” and wrong â€” for a very specific reason.

The key intuition (plain English)
Each press adds two things at the same time:

One penny of value

One new claimant to that value

So while time goes to infinity,
the amount each existing token gets from each new press shrinks.

Faster than your intuition expects.

Walk it step by step
First press (Alice)
1 token exists

Penny is split 1 way

Alice gets 1 penny

Second press (Bob)
2 tokens exist

Penny is split 2 ways

Alice gets Â½ penny

Third press
3 tokens

Alice gets â…“ penny

Millionth press
1,000,000 tokens

Alice gets 1 / 1,000,000 penny

Billionth press
1,000,000,000 tokens

Alice gets 1 / 1,000,000,000 penny

The crucial observation
Yes, presses can continue forever.

But:

The amount Alice gets per press is shrinking

And it shrinks fast enough that the total stays bounded

You are not stacking pennies.
You are stacking fractions of pennies that get smaller and smaller.

Why this doesnâ€™t blow up (the honest reason)
The system obeys this rule:

Value added per step = 1 penny
Claims added per step = 1 token

So claims scale linearly with value, not slower.

Thatâ€™s the entire reason infinite dividends do not appear.

If claims grew slower than value, you would get infinite payouts.

But they donâ€™t.

The â€œahaâ€ phrased cleanly
Hereâ€™s the sentence that matters:

Aliceâ€™s first token does not earn infinite dividends because each new payment dilutes her claim at the same rate that new value is introduced.

Thatâ€™s it.

No asymptotes required.

Optional math intuition (one line, no intimidation)
What Alice receives over time is:

1 + Â½ + â…“ + Â¼ + â€¦

This grows forever â€” but very slowly.

Even after:

1 billion presses â†’ ~21 pennies

1 trillion presses â†’ ~28 pennies

â€œInfiniteâ€ exists only on paper, not in practice.

Why this structure is actually elegant
This scheme has some rare properties:

No fixed supply

No collapse condition

No runaway winner

No hard cap required

No belief needed

Early users win a bit more, not infinitely more.
Late users are diluted, but never zeroed.
Everyoneâ€™s incentives decay smoothly.

Final grounding statement (this is the core truth)
Infinite time does not imply infinite value when dilution scales with participation.

This is the same reason:

cities donâ€™t make infinite rent per citizen

roads donâ€™t make infinite toll per driver

protocols donâ€™t explode just because theyâ€™re popular

