ChatGPT said:
Yes â€” in the context of Ordinal Theory / Ordinals on Bitcoin/BSV, satoshis do get unique, sequential identifiers, and thatâ€™s exactly what makes them useful as token identifiers. 

Hereâ€™s how it works:

ğŸ”¹ Do ordinals assign unique sequential IDs?
Yes. Ordinal Theory assigns a unique ordinal number to each individual satoshi based on the order it was mined.

The first satoshi in the very first block gets ordinal 0, the next gets 1, and so on in strict sequence. 

This gives you a numeric ID that uniquely identifies that satoshi throughout its lifecycle (unless destroyed or reâ€‘treated under specific rules). 

This serial number is what people call the â€œordinalâ€: a literal serial number for a satoshi. 

ğŸ”¹ What about 1Sat Ordinals on BSV?
On BSV the 1SatOrdinals implementation builds on the same concept: each satoshi can be tracked as a distinct unit with an underlying ordinal ID.

A satoshi that becomes a 1SatOrdinal is typically one satoshi in a UTXO; the ordinal identifies it and carries the metadata or inscription. 

The protocol uses the original ordinal number of the satoshi as part of the identification scheme. 

In short:

The ordinal number itself is a unique sequential identifier for a satoshi

Protocols like 1SatOrdinals leverage that to tie metadata/inscriptions to a specific satoshi

That ordinal number does not exist natively in Bitcoin Core â€” itâ€™s imposed by the Ordinals indexing convention â€” but it does faithfully track each satoshi across transactions as long as the Ordinals/1Sat tooling is used. 

ğŸ“Œ What this means for your use case
Because each satoshi can be given an ordinal number (a unique sequential ID), you can use this as a token ID for things like:

tokenized share certificates

collectible bonds

limited series tokens

experiential receipts tied to specific satoshis

This gives you true uniqueness even without a separate token contract standard â€” the ordinal itself is the ID.

ğŸ§  Important nuance
Ordinal IDs are not part of the Bitcoin protocol layer itself â€” theyâ€™re defined by the Ordinal Theory convention, and tools maintain the mapping. 

That means your tooling (wallet/explorer/indexer) needs to understand ordinals to track these IDs reliably. But from a practical point of view in your token system, they do function as unique IDs.

âœ… Summary:
Yes â€” in Ordinal Theory, each satoshi has a unique sequential ordinal number assigned based on the order it was created and moved. 1Sat Ordinals on BSV leverage this, so you can use these ordinal numbers as consistent, unique token IDs. 

