Tokens, Staking, and Share Certificates
A Practical Description of How Ownership Works
This document describes how ownership, transfer, and dividends function in a system that uses tokens, staking, and certificated shares. It is not an investment solicitation and does not make claims about returns. It explains mechanics only.

1. The authoritative record
The register of members is the sole authoritative record of share ownership.

Voting rights, dividends, and legal title attach only to names recorded on the register.

Tokens, dashboards, PDFs, and blockchain records are not authoritative.

This is consistent with UK company law and standard corporate practice.

Practical reason:
There must be exactly one source of legal truth. The register fulfils that role.

2. Tokens are bearer instruments, not shares
Tokens are transferable bearer objects.

They may be held, transferred, or traded without identification.

Holding a token alone confers no shareholder rights.

Tokens do not represent equity unless and until they are staked and recognised by the company.

Practical reason:
Bearer transferability enables liquidity and secondary markets without requiring company involvement.

3. Staking converts tokens into conditional equity
When a token holder chooses to stake tokens:

The holder submits identification (KYC).

The company recognises the stake.

A corresponding number of shares is entered on the register of members.

The tokens are locked and cannot be withdrawn while staked.

At this point:

The holder becomes a shareholder.

Dividends and voting rights attach.

The company may issue a share certificate as evidence.

Practical reason:
Equity rights require a known counterparty. Staking is the moment identity is asserted.

4. Unstaking reverses the process
When a shareholder unstake their tokens:

Shares are removed from the register.

The tokens are unlocked and returned.

Any issued share certificate is revoked and becomes void.

After unstaking:

The former holder is no longer a shareholder.

No dividends or voting rights remain.

Any physical or digital certificate has no legal effect.

Practical reason:
The company must always be able to reconcile issued shares with the register.

5. What a share certificate is (and is not)
A share certificate is evidence, not ownership.

It evidences that a person was entered on the register at the time of issue.

It does not override the register.

It does not survive revocation or unstaking.

Practical reason:
Certificates exist for compatibility with legal, accounting, and investor expectations.

6. Transfer of certificated shares
A share certificate may be transferred between third parties by endorsement:

The current holder signs the certificate assigning it to another party.

The certificate may change hands multiple times.

No rights transfer until the company recognises the transfer.

When presented to the company:

The endorsement chain is verified.

The register is updated.

A new certificate is issued.

The old certificate is cancelled.

Practical reason:
This allows off-platform transfers while preserving a single authoritative register.

7. Certificates and revocation
If a shareholder unstaked tokens or otherwise exits:

Their certificate is revoked.

The register no longer lists them.

Any retained copy of the certificate is void.

The company will not honour certificates that do not correspond to the current register.

Practical reason:
Preventing stale or duplicated claims requires revocability.

8. Dividends
Dividends are paid only to shareholders recorded on the register at the relevant date.

Token holders who have not staked receive no dividends.

Endorsed but unregistered transferees receive no dividends.

Dividends follow the register, not the token or certificate.

Practical reason:
Dividend payment requires certainty about the recipient.

9. Failure scenarios
If the company ceases trading:

Staked tokens represent claims on a failed entity.

Share certificates have no residual value.

Tokens do not become bearer claims on company assets.

Practical reason:
Equity risk cannot be eliminated by tokenisation.

10. Why certificates exist at all
Certificates are retained for three practical reasons:

Familiarity for investors and auditors

Evidence in disputes

Support for private, off-platform transfers

They are not required for:

cap table integrity

dividend calculation

legal ownership

Summary (plain facts)
Tokens are bearer, liquid, and non-authoritative.

Staking is the moment equity is created.

The register is the only source of legal truth.

Certificates are optional evidence, revocable, and secondary.

Unstaking destroys equity and voids certificates.

Dividends follow the register, not the blockchain.

If you want, next we can:

formalise the staking / unstaking state machine

specify dividend record-date mechanics

design certificate numbering vs batching

or translate this into terms of service language

But as a neutral statement of reality, this is already clean, defensible, and internally consistent.

