ChatGPT said:
Short answer: yes â€” conceptually youâ€™re exactly right.
A tokenised share certificate maps very cleanly onto the UTXO model.

But there are two layers to separate: cryptographic transfer vs legal recognition.

1. Does a tokenised certificate map to UTXOs?
The old paper world
Paper certificate model:

Certificate = unique bearer instrument

Ownership = whoever physically holds it

Transfer = endorsement (signature on the back)

Chain of endorsements = proof of provenance

Company recognition = updates the register

This is effectively:

A unique object

With a history of transfers

That moves between parties

Where possession matters

The UTXO world
A UTXO is:

A uniquely identifiable output

Owned by whoever controls the private key

Transferable without issuer involvement

With an immutable transaction history

Chain of custody built into the ledger

Mapping:

Paper Certificate	UTXO / Token
Unique certificate	Unique token / ordinal
Physical possession	Private key control
Signature on the back	Cryptographic signature
Chain of endorsements	Transaction history
Bearer instrument	Bearer token
Presented to company	Presented for redemption/staking
So yes:

A tokenised share certificate is a near-perfect digital analogue of a certificated bearer share.

In fact, Bitcoinâ€™s UTXO model was historically inspired by bearer instruments.

2. Can it be â€œsigned as itâ€™s soldâ€?
Hereâ€™s the nuance:

Cryptographically
Each transfer is already signed.

The blockchain already records provenance.

No extra endorsement is needed.

The transaction itself is the endorsement.

So:

Sending the token = signing the transfer

Transaction history = endorsement chain

Legally
The company still must:

verify the presented token

verify the presenterâ€™s identity

update the register

issue a new certificate (if certificated regime is retained)

Because:

Legal title follows the register, not possession alone.

The token is evidence, not authoritative ownership.

3. What your model enables (and why itâ€™s elegant)
If you embed the PDF certificate inside the token:

You get:

One token = one certificate

Cryptographic chain of custody

Immutable provenance

Bearer transfer

Off-platform secondary markets

No need for physical endorsements

Natural mapping to Bitcoin primitives

Auditability

Revocability via register updates

It becomes:

A digital bearer share certificate

With automatic endorsement history

And a reconciliation step at redemption

This is structurally cleaner than the paper system.

4. Important constraint (not a blocker)
Even if tokenised:

The company is not obligated to recognise the holder until:

identity is provided

staking/redemption occurs

the register is updated

So the flow becomes:

Certificate minted into token

Token moves freely between wallets

Holder presents it

Company verifies

Register updated

Old certificate revoked

New certificate optionally issued

Which is exactly the same as paper â€” just cryptographically enforced.

5. Your intuition is correct
Your instinct is spot on:

Paper endorsement chains â‰ˆ UTXO history

Bearer certificates â‰ˆ bearer tokens

Possession â‰ˆ key control

Signing the back â‰ˆ signing a transaction

This is not a stretch. Itâ€™s a direct lineage.

Bitcoin behaves more like:

cash

bearer bonds

warehouse receipts

share certificates

â€¦than like accounts or balances.

6. One practical note
If you do this, best practice is:

One certificate per token (granular, not batched)

Token contains:

certificate PDF

serial number

issuance metadata

hash of register entry

Register remains authoritative

Redemption/staking burns or locks token

This preserves:

liquidity

transferability

auditability

legal coherence

Conclusion
Yes:

Tokenised share certificates map extremely well to UTXOs.

Transfer between wallets is the digital equivalent of endorsement.

Transaction history is the endorsement chain.

Possession maps to key control.

The register remains the legal authority.

Your model is internally consistent and historically grounded.

