Below is a Product Requirements Document you can drop straight into your IDE and hand to an LLM or human engineer.

PRD: bit/sign â€” Cryptographically Anchored Share Certificate Issuance & Verification
1. Purpose
bit/sign is a certificate issuance and verification system that binds:

a human-recognisable handwritten director signature

to a cryptographic identity

and a blockchain-verifiable issuance event

The goal is to issue legally recognisable share certificates that:

look like traditional certificates,

are readable by humans and lawyers,

are cryptographically verifiable,

and integrate with a token-based staking system.

bit/sign does not define legal ownership.
Legal ownership is defined exclusively by the companyâ€™s register of members.

Certificates are evidence, not title.

2. Non-Goals
bit/sign explicitly does not:

determine ownership of shares

replace the register of members

enforce dividends or voting rights

act as a custody wallet

provide dynamic or mutable on-chain metadata

create a â€œsecurity tokenâ€ system

3. Core Concepts & Definitions
3.1 Register of Members (Authoritative)
Maintained by the company

Defines legal ownership of shares

Updated only upon:

staking + KYC

redemption of a valid certificate

board-authorised corporate action

3.2 Share Certificate (Evidence)
A digitally generated PDF

Signed by a director

Represents that:

at a point in time

a named individual

was entered on the register

for a specific number/class of shares

Certificates can be:

issued

transferred privately

presented for redemption

revoked

3.3 Ordinal / Token (Optional Carrier)
A unique satoshi (ordinal) may embed:

the certificate PDF

or a hash/reference to it

The token is:

a bearer object

transferable without company involvement

Possession of the token does not imply legal ownership

4. Director Signature Model
4.1 Canonical Signature Asset
Each director has one canonical handwritten signature

Created by:

physical signing

high-resolution scan

Stored as:

PNG (transparent background)

This signature is:

visually consistent

human-recognisable

legally attributable

4.2 Signature Anchoring
The PNG is hashed (e.g. SHA-256)

The hash is:

published publicly

optionally anchored on-chain

This creates an immutable fingerprint of the signature

The visible signature must never change.
Authority comes from consistency, not secrecy.

5. Certificate Issuance Flow
5.1 Preconditions
Investor has:

staked tokens

completed KYC

Company has:

approved registration

updated the register of members

5.2 Certificate Generation
For each issuance:

The system generates a PDF containing:

Company name & registration number

Certificate serial number

Share class

Number of shares

Shareholder legal name

Date of issuance

Director printed name

Visible handwritten signature image

Reference to:

signature hash

issuance transaction / internal ID

5.3 Cryptographic Attestation
The hash of the certificate PDF is signed using:

the directorâ€™s wallet private key

This signature is stored:

on-chain or

in the company database with a public verification endpoint

This cryptographic signature:

proves director authorisation

proves certificate integrity

does not replace the visual signature

6. Certificate Transfer Model (Off-Register)
Certificates may be transferred privately between third parties

Transfers occur by:

token transfer (UTXO)

or off-chain agreement

The company does not track these transfers

The register remains unchanged

The certificate functions as:

a bearer receipt

capable of endorsement via cryptographic transfer history

7. Certificate Redemption Flow
7.1 Presentation
A redeemer submits:

the certificate (PDF or ordinal)

cryptographic proof of possession

their identity (KYC)

7.2 Verification
The company verifies:

