You said:
Explain something to me here: 

I write my signature. I scan it. Then publish it in an Op_Return? 

Can the png be pruned? 

Iâ€™ve got a hash of the TX with the PNG data in it so I can always show the PNG and if it matches the hash on chain weâ€™re goodâ€¦ 

But the png on chain itself? Pruned= gone. Right?
ChatGPT said:
Great question â€” and youâ€™re asking it at exactly the right level.
Letâ€™s separate what is guaranteed, what is not, and what you should actually rely on.

Short answer up front:

Yes, the PNG data itself can be pruned.
No, that does not break your scheme.
And you should not rely on on-chain persistence of the PNG anyway.

Now letâ€™s be precise.

1. What OP_RETURN (or inscription data) actually guarantees
When you put data (PNG bytes) into a transaction:

The transaction hash commits to the exact bytes

The bytes are part of the transaction at the time it is mined

Anyone validating the transaction at that time sees the data

What is guaranteed forever:

âœ… the TXID
âœ… the Merkle commitment
âœ… the hash of the data

What is not guaranteed forever:

âŒ the raw data payload being retrievable from every node

This is true on every blockchain, including BSV.

2. Can the PNG be pruned?
Yes â€” absolutely.
Pruning means:

A node discards old transaction data

Keeps only what it needs to validate the UTXO set

Old payloads may no longer be locally available

So:

The commitment remains

The data may be gone from that node

This is expected behaviour, not a failure.

3. Important distinction: pruning â‰  erasure
Pruning does not mean:

the data never existed

the commitment is invalid

the proof is broken

It means:

â€œThis node no longer stores a copy.â€

Other nodes may still have it.
Archival services may still have it.
Your own backups may still have it.

4. Your reasoning is correct (and sufficient)
You said:

â€œIâ€™ve got a hash of the TX with the PNG data in it so I can always show the PNG and if it matches the hash on chain weâ€™re goodâ€¦â€

âœ… Correct. That is the correct security model.

This is classic cryptographic notarisation:

Chain = timestamped commitment

Off-chain = artefact storage

Hash = binding glue

This is how:

document notarisation works

legal timestamping works

most â€œon-chain documentsâ€ work in practice

5. The mistake to avoid
Do not think of the chain as:

â€œPermanent file storageâ€

Think of it as:

Permanent proof that something existed, unmodified, at a given time

If you rely on:

â€œthe PNG must always be retrievable from the chainâ€

you are building on sand.

If you rely on:

â€œthe chain proves integrity and authorshipâ€

you are building on rock.

6. The correct bit/sign pattern (recommended)
What goes on-chain
Hash of the canonical signature PNG

Possibly:

director public key

statement of intent

version identifier

This is small, cheap, permanent.

What stays off-chain
The PNG itself

Stored in:

company records

backups

certificate PDFs

investor dashboards

Verification flow
Extract PNG from certificate

Hash it

Compare to on-chain hash

Verify director cryptographic signature

Done

Even if:

every node prunes the original PNG bytes
you still win.

7. Why this is legally better
Courts do not want:

â€œtrust the blockchain nodeâ€

They want:

evidence

provenance

reproducibility

verification

Your scheme provides:

human-recognisable signature

cryptographic integrity

public timestamp

independence from any single database

Thatâ€™s ideal.

8. One more subtle but important point
If you did rely on on-chain PNG availability:

you would introduce dependency on:

miner policies

archival economics

third-party indexers

By not relying on it, you avoid all of that.

9. Final answer, condensed
Yes, OP_RETURN / inscription data can be pruned

Pruning does not remove the cryptographic commitment

Your hash-based verification model is correct

You should not rely on raw on-chain PNG persistence

Use the chain as a notary, not a filesystem

Youâ€™re designing this the right way.

If you want next, we can:

formalise the on-chain anchoring statement

decide exactly what bytes get hashed

or spec a verification UI flow (â€œhow a lawyer checks this in 60 secondsâ€)

