You said:
Wee did some REALLY good work yesterday. However when I checked out my first blog post on Bitcoin writer this morning I discovered two problems with it, heres the copy; can you see what the two problems are? â€œBitcoin Writer is a word processor that saves your documents to the blockchain.
It works like any writing tool you've used before. You open it, you write, you save. The difference is where your words end up. Instead of a file on your hard drive or a folder in someone else's cloud, your document is written directly to the Bitcoin blockchain. Permanently. Immutably. Yours.
Every time you save, you pay a small fee - a fraction of a penny, enough to cover the transaction cost. In return, you receive $bWriter tokens.
There are one billion tokens in total. Each token entitles the holder to a proportional share of the platform's revenue, paid as dividends in Bitcoin. The more people use Bitcoin Writer, the more revenue it generates, the more valuable each token becomes.
Write, save, own.
Why Write to the Blockchain?
Most of what we write today exists at the mercy of platforms. Documents live on servers we don't control, governed by terms of service we didn't read, subject to deletion policies we weren't consulted on. Companies go bankrupt. Services shut down. Accounts get terminated. The words remain until they don't.
The blockchain offers something different: permanence. A document saved to Bitcoin cannot be altered after the fact. It cannot be quietly deleted. It cannot be lost because a startup ran out of runway or a cloud provider had an outage. The document exists for as long as the chain exists, which - if Bitcoin fulfils its promise - means forever.
This permanence has practical applications. Timestamps on the blockchain are immutable, which means you can prove you wrote something at a specific moment in time. For intellectual property, for contracts, for research, for any situation where priority matters, this is valuable. "I wrote this first" becomes a verifiable claim rather than an assertion.
There's also the question of censorship. Platforms decide what speech they'll host. Sometimes those decisions are reasonable, sometimes they aren't, but either way the power sits with the platform. A document on the blockchain answers to no content policy. Once it's written, it's there. No one can make it disappear.
Business Applications
The characteristics that make blockchain storage interesting for personal writing become essential for certain categories of business document.
Legal documents. A will saved to the blockchain exists independently of the solicitor who drafted it, the filing cabinet it was stored in, or the house that contained the filing cabinet. It cannot be tampered with after signing. Its timestamp is beyond dispute. When the moment comes to execute it, there's no question of what the testator intended or when they intended it - the document speaks for itself, immutably.
Contracts. Every contract is ultimately a question of "what did we agree, and when did we agree it?" The blockchain answers both questions definitively. No more disputes about which version was signed. No more concerns about one party quietly altering terms. The agreement exists on-chain exactly as it was written, timestamped to the second, unchangeable by either party. For employment contracts, property agreements, commercial terms, partnership deeds - anywhere that trust is required, the blockchain provides it mathematically rather than institutionally.
Corporate records. Board minutes, shareholder resolutions, articles of association. These documents define what a company is and what it has decided. Their integrity matters. A complete corporate history on the blockchain is auditable by anyone, verifiable instantly, and immune to the kind of "we can't find that document" problems that plague disputes years after the fact.
Intellectual property. The moment you save your screenplay, your research paper, your design, your code - that moment is recorded permanently. Prior art becomes provable. Authorship becomes undeniable. The blockchain doesn't replace patents or copyright, but it provides evidence that no court can dispute.
Regulatory filings. When compliance requires proving you filed something at a particular time, the blockchain is the ultimate receipt. No reliance on postal records or email timestamps. The document exists on-chain at a specific block height, and that block height corresponds to a specific moment in time, permanently.
Why Tokens?
The people who use Bitcoin Writer should own Bitcoin Writer.
This seems obvious when you say it out loud, but it's the opposite of how most platforms work. Typically, users create all the value - their content, their attention, their network effects - and shareholders capture it. The people who built the thing and the people who use the thing are different populations with different interests.
Tokens change this. If you're paying to save documents, you should benefit when others do the same. Your usage earns you ownership. Your ownership appreciates as usage grows. Incentives align.
The tokens aren't sold to anonymous users. They're earned through contribution. You use the platform, you receive equity as compensation. This isn't speculation on someone else's work - it's participation in something you're actively building.
And the token itself is simple. One token, one right: receive dividends. No governance complexity, no staking mechanics, no convoluted utility token economics. Just straightforward ownership of a revenue-generating platform.
The Distribution Curve
Not all users are equal, and the token distribution reflects this.
Early adoption is risky. When a platform is new, unproven, possibly destined to fail, the people who use it anyway are taking a chance. They deserve to be rewarded disproportionately if that chance pays off.
Bitcoin understood this. The block reward started at 50 BTC and halves every four years. Early miners received far more coins per unit of work than later miners. This wasn't unfair - it was compensation for the risk and uncertainty of participating when success was far from guaranteed.
Bitcoin Writer follows the same principle. Token distribution follows a Taylor series curve - front-loaded, declining over time, asymptotically approaching zero. The first users to save documents receive substantially more tokens per transaction than those who come later. As the platform matures and the risk diminishes, so does the reward.
This creates the right incentives. Early adopters are rewarded for their faith. Later users still earn tokens, still become owners, but they're arriving at something proven rather than something speculative. Their smaller reward reflects their smaller risk.
It also ensures scarcity. The billion token cap is real. As the curve flattens, tokens become harder to earn. The ownership structure ossifies. At some point, the only way to acquire meaningful stake is to buy from someone who got there earlier.
This is fair. This is how risk and reward should work. The people who believed first should benefit most.
How Dividends Work
Revenue flows in as Bitcoin. Dividends flow out as Bitcoin.
The platform calculates each token holder's proportional share and sends payments directly to on-chain addresses. No bank account in the middle. No payment processor taking a cut. No forms to fill out. Just satoshis arriving in your wallet, proportional to your stake.
This is what Bitcoin was designed for - programmable money moving between parties without intermediaries. Bitcoin Writer simply applies that principle to equity ownership and dividend distribution.
Try It
Bitcoin Writer will be live at bitcoin-writer.com.
Write something. Save it to the chain. See what ownership feels like.

