Bitcoin Writer
Bitcoin Writer is a word processor that saves your documents to the Bitcoin blockchain.

You open it. You write. You save.
The difference is where your words go.

Instead of a file on your hard drive or a folder in someone elseâ€™s cloud, your document is written directly to the Bitcoin blockchain. Permanently. Immutably. Independently of any company, platform, or service continuing to exist.

This matters more than it first appears.

The Blockchain as a Permanent Human Record
For most of history, the survival of writing has depended on institutions.

Books survived because libraries were funded.
Contracts survived because courts existed.
Records survived because archives were maintained.
Speech survived because platforms allowed it.

When institutions fail, writing disappears with them.

The Bitcoin blockchain is the first writing surface in history that does not belong to an institution. It has no editor, no content policy, no archive room to burn down, no company that can go bankrupt and take the data with it.

It is a time-ordered, append-only record shared by the entire world.

In practical terms, this means that anything written to it becomes part of a permanent global record â€” a kind of digital totem pole that any human can add to, but no one can erase.

This has obvious value for things like last wills and testaments, witness statements, political speech, research, creative work, and historical records. It also has value for more ordinary writing: notes, drafts, essays, thoughts you donâ€™t want to lose or have rewritten later.

Bitcoin Writer exists to make writing to that permanent record simple.

How It Works
Bitcoin Writer behaves like a normal writing tool.

You write a document.
You save it.
A small Bitcoin transaction is created.

The transaction fee is tiny â€” a fraction of a penny â€” just enough to pay for recording your words on the blockchain. The document is timestamped, ordered, and becomes immutable.

Once written, it cannot be altered, quietly deleted, or lost because a service shut down. As long as the Bitcoin blockchain exists, the document exists.

Each save produces an on-chain proof of authorship and time. â€œI wrote this at this momentâ€ becomes a verifiable fact, not an assertion.

Participation and Tokens
Every time a document is written to the blockchain using Bitcoin Writer, the system issues a cryptographic token.

This token is not required to use the software.
It is not required to read or prove authorship.
It exists as a record of participation.

Tokens are issued on a fixed, asymptotic curve. Early participation is rewarded more heavily than later participation, reflecting the greater uncertainty of using a system before it is proven. Over time, issuance declines and eventually approaches zero.

There is a hard cap on the total number of tokens.

This same token is earned by people who write, and may also be acquired by people who support the project in other ways. There is no separate class for â€œusersâ€ and â€œinvestorsâ€. Participation is participation.

Registration, Ownership, and Dividends
Bitcoin Writer is operated by a company.

That company earns revenue when people write, publish, encrypt, decrypt, and sell access to their work. Revenue is earned in Bitcoin.

Token ownership by itself does not place anyone on the companyâ€™s cap table.

To be recognised as an owner, a token holder must choose to register and stake their tokens with the company. Registration requires identification and places the holder on the official register of members.

Registered token holders may receive dividends.

Dividends, when paid, are paid in Bitcoin and are proportional to registered holdings. Unregistered tokens do not receive dividends. This distinction is deliberate and reflects how ownership works in practice: recognition requires a register.

Token holders may register, unregister, stake, or unstake according to the published terms. Ownership is not forced. Participation does not require registration.

Certificates and Evidence
When tokens are registered, the company issues evidence of registration.

This may take the form of digitally signed share certificates, reflecting established corporate practice. Certificates are evidence of title, not the source of it. The authoritative record is the companyâ€™s register.

Certificates may be replaced, revoked, or reissued as registration status changes. This allows ownership to be updated cleanly if tokens are unstaked, transferred, or re-registered.

The system is designed to be legible both to humans and to existing legal frameworks.

Why This Structure Exists
The primary purpose of Bitcoin Writer is not speculation.

It is to give people a way to write to a permanent, neutral, global record â€” one that does not depend on permission from platforms, states, or companies.

The ownership structure exists to ensure that the people who use and sustain the system are the people who ultimately benefit from it. Writing creates value. Usage creates revenue. Participation creates ownership.

This is not about short-term price movement. It is about long-term continuity.

Try It
Bitcoin Writer will be available at bitcoin-writer.com.

Write something that matters.
Save it to the chain.
Take part in the permanent human record.

Ownership, if you want it, is there to be claimed.

