Bitcoin Writer
Bitcoin Writer is a writing tool that records documents on the Bitcoin blockchain.

You open it.
You write.
You save.

When you save, your document is committed to Bitcoin â€” not as a file owned by a platform, but as a cryptographic record embedded in the worldâ€™s most durable public ledger.

That distinction matters.

Writing That Outlives Platforms
Most writing today exists at the pleasure of institutions.

Documents live on company servers.
They are governed by terms of service.
They disappear when accounts are closed, services shut down, or companies fail.

Bitcoin offers something different.

The Bitcoin blockchain is a neutral, append-only record shared by the entire world. It has no editor, no content policy, and no administrator who can revise history. Once data is committed, its existence and timestamp can be proven forever.

Bitcoin Writer exists to make that permanence usable.

What â€œPermanentâ€ Actually Means
When you save a document with Bitcoin Writer, the system produces a Bitcoin transaction that cryptographically commits to your work at a specific moment in time.

This guarantees three things:

Integrity â€“ the document cannot be altered without detection

Ordering â€“ it is provably earlier or later than other records

Timestamping â€“ its existence at a specific time is beyond dispute

These properties do not depend on Bitcoin Writer continuing to exist. They are enforced by the Bitcoin network itself.

Availability â€” the ability to retrieve full document content easily â€” is a service. Bitcoin Writer provides that service, alongside indexing, encryption, access control, and retrieval. The blockchain provides the proof.

Why This Matters
This kind of permanence has real-world applications:

Authorship & prior art â€“ proving you wrote something first

Legal records â€“ wills, agreements, statements, attestations

Research & journalism â€“ immutable publication timelines

Creative work â€“ a permanent public record of expression

Bitcoin Writer does not replace courts, libraries, or archives. It gives them something theyâ€™ve never had before: cryptographic certainty.

The Service Model
Bitcoin Writer is not a charity and not a miner fee passthrough.

Users pay for a service that includes:

document processing and encoding

encryption and access control

Bitcoin transaction creation and fee management

indexing and retrieval

long-term archival availability

a usable writing interface

The blockchain write is the settlement layer.
The product is the service wrapped around it.

This revenue sustains the company.

Participation and Tokens
When people use Bitcoin Writer, the system issues cryptographic tokens according to a fixed, asymptotic schedule.

Early participation is rewarded more heavily than later participation. As the system matures and uncertainty falls, issuance declines and eventually ends.

There is a hard cap on the total supply.

Tokens are issued to people who use and support the system. There is no separate class of â€œuserâ€ and â€œinvestorâ€. Participation is participation.

The blockchain transaction itself is the receipt for writing. Tokens are not receipts; they are a record of early contribution.

Registration, Ownership, and Dividends
Bitcoin Writer is operated by a company that earns revenue from its services.

Token ownership alone does not place anyone on the companyâ€™s cap table.

To be recognised as an owner, a token holder must choose to register and stake their tokens with the company. Registration requires identification and places the holder on the official register of members.

Registered token holders may receive dividends.

Dividends, when paid, are paid in Bitcoin and are proportional to registered holdings. Unregistered tokens do not receive dividends.

Participation does not require registration. Ownership does.

Evidence and Certificates
When tokens are registered, the company issues formal evidence of registration, consistent with established corporate practice.

These certificates are evidence of title. The authoritative record of ownership is the companyâ€™s register. Certificates may be issued, replaced, or revoked as registration status changes.

This structure is designed to be legible to existing legal systems while remaining native to Bitcoin.

A Permanent Record, A Finite Company
The Bitcoin blockchain does not need Bitcoin Writer to exist.

The record outlives the platform.

Bitcoin Writer exists to make that record usable, searchable, and accessible â€” and to provide a commercial structure around it that can endure, evolve, and be held accountable.

Writing to the permanent human record should not require permission.
Using a well-built service to do so is a choice.

