2. Technical Appendix â€” How This Actually Works
Permanence vs Availability
Bitcoin guarantees:

ordering

timestamping

integrity

It does not guarantee long-term availability of arbitrary data from every node.

Bitcoin Writer addresses this by:

committing documents cryptographically to Bitcoin

operating redundant archival infrastructure

allowing independent third parties to mirror content

Even if all services disappear, the proof remains.

OP_RETURN, Pruning, and Data Strategy
Some transaction data may be pruned by nodes.

This does not invalidate:

inclusion proofs

timestamps

document hashes

Bitcoin Writer treats the blockchain as:

the source of truth for existence and order

not the sole storage medium

This distinction allows scalability without false claims.

Tokens and Asymptotic Issuance
Tokens follow a declining issuance curve with a fixed cap.

This ensures:

early risk is rewarded

ownership stabilises over time

the service does not depend on perpetual issuance

Once issuance ends:

writing continues

revenue continues

ownership is fixed

This mirrors how real-world equity works.

Registration and Legal Ownership
Ownership is determined by:

the companyâ€™s register of members

Tokens are bearer instruments until registered.

Registration:

requires identification

places the holder on the cap table

enables dividend eligibility

Unstaking removes the holder from the register and returns shares to treasury.

Certificates are evidence, not authority.

Why a Company Exists at All
Bitcoin does not need companies.

People do.

The company provides:

usability

continuity

legal accountability

dividend distribution

service guarantees

The blockchain provides:

truth

order

permanence

Each does what it is good at.

