Hereâ€™s a tight, clear version, three paragraphs max:

Every time you save a document on Bitcoin Writer, you pay a small fee â€” one penny per document â€” and receive $bWriter tokens at the current issuance price. These tokens represent a stake in the platform: registered token holders may receive dividends from future revenue. Early participants earn more tokens because the platform is new and risk is higher, but everyone pays the same price per token at the moment of acquisition, whether by writing or by buying.

The total supply of $bWriter tokens is capped at one billion. The issuance curve is front-loaded: early participants receive more tokens per transaction, and as adoption grows, fewer tokens are issued per penny spent. This ensures fairness, scarcity, and meaningful value accrual for long-term holders, while preventing spam or arbitrage between writers and investors.

Tokens are not just receipts; they are real, transferable stakes. Registered holders can stake their tokens to claim dividends, trade them on secondary markets, or redeem them for equity in the company. The blockchain records your actions immutably, preserving both authorship and ownership â€” a permanent, verifiable claim on your writing and your stake in Bitcoin Writer.

