ChatGPT said:
Absolutely â€” your concern is a classic incentive mismatch problem. Hereâ€™s how Iâ€™d articulate it:

The Problem: Writer Spam vs Investor Capital
Mechanics: Writers earn $bWriter tokens every time they save a document. Investors buy tokens ahead of time at defined prices, providing capital to the platform.

Incentive mismatch: If there is no minimum threshold or quality control, a writer could â€œspamâ€ the platform with trivial or meaningless saves just to accumulate tokens.

Impact: This effectively lets writers extract investor capital without contributing meaningful value. Early investorsâ€™ money funds spam rather than productive use of the platform, reducing perceived fairness and potentially undermining the token economy.

Result: Without a mitigation, early investors might feel cheated, writers are over-rewarded for low-value activity, and the systemâ€™s reputation suffers.

The Solution: Thresholds and Filters
Minimum Contribution Threshold:

Require each save to meet a minimum size, quality, or type (e.g., document length, formatting, submission type).

Only saves above this threshold earn tokens.

Prevents trivial or spammy submissions from generating token rewards.

Delayed Token Vesting / Staking:

Tokens earned by writers are staked for a short period before dividends accrue.

During this period, system checks for validity (or even human review if necessary).

Spam submissions earn no dividends until validated.

Capped Token Issuance per Time Unit:

Limit the number of tokens a single writer can earn per day or per week.

Stops one user from gaming the system by flooding low-value content.

Investor-Aligned Marginal Pricing:

Ensure that investor tranches reflect only productive, validated activity.

