ChatGPT said:
Ah â€” yes, this is exactly the kind of thing you need to scrutinize before publishing. Letâ€™s break it down carefully.

Claim: â€œyour work is written immutably on-chain. Permanently. Yours.â€
Reality check:

Bitcoin SV on-chain storage

Yes, BSV allows you to store arbitrary data using OP_RETURN or similar methods.

Once confirmed in a block, the data is included in the blockchain.

Practical immutability

Data is technically permanent as long as the blockchain exists.

But if you store data in a prunable way (e.g., using nodes that prune OP_RETURN data to save disk space), some full nodes may not keep it forever.

Implication: â€œpermanentâ€ is true if you or someone else maintains full nodes that never prune your data. Otherwise, casual access may fail.

Ownership

Storing data on-chain doesnâ€™t automatically confer legal ownership.

The token system ($bWriter) can confer economic and governance rights, but the raw document itself isnâ€™t â€œyoursâ€ legally unless linked to an enforceable contract or registration system.

Practical permanence vs. user expectation

If you imply that anyone can retrieve and verify it at any time, that may not hold unless you also provide:

Your own full node or archival service

Verification tools (hashes, proofs)

Otherwise, someone could â€œloseâ€ access even though the data is technically on-chain.

âœ… Bottom line:

Technically, yes â€” the document is on-chain.

Practically, you need non-prunable storage and verification tools to make â€œpermanently retrievableâ€ true.

Ownership claims must be tied to your token and registration system.

Suggested rewrite for the blog:

â€œOpen it, write, save â€” just like any other writing tool. Instead of storing files on your hard drive or in someone else's cloud, your document is recorded on the Bitcoin blockchain. With our system, you can verify it, retrieve it, and assert your stake via $bWriter tokens. Permanently accessible, cryptographically verifiable, and linked to you.â€

