You said:
Thatâ€™s no good. Is there a way of storing it permanently on chain without our company?
ChatGPT said:
Yes â€” but itâ€™s subtle. Letâ€™s break it down carefully. There are ways to make documents truly permanent on-chain, independent of your company acting as an archival service, but it comes with trade-offs:

1. Native BSV storage
You can embed the data directly in a transaction using OP_RETURN or data push.

Once mined, the transaction is on the blockchain forever.

Problem:

Many nodes prune non-financial data (to save space).

So technically it exists on-chain, but not every node will keep it.

2. Full-node archival
Some people/organizations run fully validating, archival nodes that store every byte ever mined.

If your document is included in a transaction, it lives permanently on these nodes, independent of your company.

The downside: users must trust or maintain access to these archival nodes.

3. Decentralized archival services
Use services like Ords/Ordinal-style permanent storage, or other blockchain data anchors.

Anyone can replicate the data and store it, and as long as someone keeps a copy, itâ€™s effectively permanent.

This is how Bitcoin itself maintains history â€” even if some nodes die, copies exist elsewhere.

4. Hash anchoring + off-chain storage
Instead of storing the entire document on-chain, store a cryptographic hash.

The document itself can live elsewhere (IPFS, S3, etc.), but anyone can prove authenticity by comparing the hash to the blockchain.

True permanence depends on redundancy of storage.

Advantage: cheap and verifiable.

Disadvantage: if the off-chain copies disappear and no one keeps them, the document is gone despite the hash.

âœ… Key takeaway
There is no 100% guarantee of retrievability without some node somewhere storing your data.

But if you publish directly to BSV in a non-prunable way, and/or rely on archival nodes run by the community or yourself, then itâ€™s effectively permanent without the company needing to maintain it.

Your company can remain just the interface and token system, not the storage guarantor.

If you want, I can draft a revised â€œpermanence paragraphâ€ for your blog thatâ€™s compelling for writers but accurate technically â€” showing that permanence is blockchain-backed and independent of the company, without over-promising.

