Why Put Writing on the Blockchain?
The internet has a problem: nothing lasts. Websites go offline. Companies shut down. Servers get wiped. That blog post you wrote in 2010? Gone. Those terms you agreed to? Changed without notice. That receipt, that contract, that letter â€” deleted, edited, or lost to time.
The blockchain is different. Once something is written to Bitcoin, it stays there. Not because a company promises to keep it online, but because the network itself â€” thousands of computers around the world â€” maintains a permanent record. No single point of failure. No terms of service. No "we've updated our policy."
When you write with Bitcoin Writer, your document becomes part of that record. A hundred years from now, anyone can verify exactly what you wrote and when you wrote it. The blockchain doesn't forget.
How It Works
Bitcoin Writer is a simple word processor. You type your document just like you would in any other app. When you're ready to publish, you click a button and pay one penny per page.
That's it. Your document goes on-chain. You receive a $bWriter token in your wallet â€” one token for every page you've written. The token contains your actual content, not just a link to it. Your writing lives inside the token itself.
The token proves you wrote it. The blockchain proves when. And because it's all public and permanent, anyone can verify both.
What Can You Write?
Anything you want to last forever.
Legal documents. Contracts, agreements, terms of service. Put them on-chain and no one can claim they were different. The timestamp proves the version. The content proves the terms.
Creative work. Poems, stories, essays, manifestos. Establish authorship permanently. No need for copyright registration â€” the blockchain is your witness.
Personal records. Letters to your future self. Messages to your children. A diary that outlives you. Write it once, and it exists forever.
Business records. Meeting notes, decisions, announcements. Create an immutable audit trail that no one can dispute.
Anything important. If it matters enough to keep, it matters enough to keep permanently.
One Penny Per Page
We charge one penny per page. That's $0.01 USD.
Why so cheap? Because the blockchain handles the hard part. We're not storing your files on expensive servers. We're not backing up your data. We're not promising uptime or availability. The network does all that automatically, forever, as part of how Bitcoin works.
We just make it easy. You write, you pay a penny, you're done.
Your Token, Your Proof
When you publish a document, you receive a $bWriter token. This isn't just a receipt â€” it's your actual content, stored on-chain inside the token itself.
Think of it like a deed to a house, except the deed contains the entire house. The token is the document. Own the token, own the document. Transfer the token, transfer the document.
You can hold your tokens in any compatible wallet. You can sell them, gift them, or keep them forever. The choice is yours.
Become a Shareholder
Want more than just the token? Stake it.
Here's how it works: complete KYC verification, stake your $bWriter tokens with us, and become a shareholder in Bitcoin Writer. Staked tokens earn dividends â€” 50% of all platform revenue, split among all stakers proportionally.
The more tokens you stake, the larger your share of the dividend pool. Every penny someone pays to write a document, half of it goes to you and the other stakers.
While your tokens are staked, we store and serve your content through our platform. You earn dividends. We cover the infrastructure costs with our 50%.
Unstake Anytime
Staking is not a lock-in. You can unstake your tokens whenever you want.
When you unstake, you get your tokens back immediately. You're removed from the cap table and stop earning dividends. We delete your data from our servers.
But here's the key: the token is still yours. Your content is still on-chain. You just manage it yourself instead of through our platform.
This is the beauty of building on Bitcoin. We can't hold your content hostage because we never controlled it in the first place. The blockchain did.
The Economics
Let's break down the numbers.
For writers: One penny per page. You get a token containing your content. If you stake, you earn dividends from every future document published on the platform.
For stakers: 50% of all revenue flows to staked token holders. The other 50% covers our costs â€” development, infrastructure, support. As the platform grows, so does the dividend pool.
For the network: Every document adds to Bitcoin's permanent record. More utility for the blockchain. More value for everyone building on it.
This isn't charity. It's aligned incentives. Writers get permanent storage. Stakers get income. We get a sustainable business. The network gets more useful.
Why Bitcoin?
We built on Bitcoin specifically, not Ethereum or Solana or any other chain. Here's why.
Bitcoin is the oldest, most secure, most decentralized blockchain in existence. It's been running continuously since 2009. It's survived attacks, controversies, forks, and countless predictions of its demise. It's still here. It will still be here.
When you're promising "forever," you need a foundation that can deliver. Bitcoin is that foundation.
We use the BSV (Bitcoin Satoshi Vision) implementation specifically because it supports the data sizes needed for documents while keeping transaction costs low. One penny per page is only possible because BSV was designed for this kind of utility.
Privacy and Publicity
Let's be clear about something: documents on Bitcoin Writer are public.
When you publish a document, anyone can read it. That's the point. The blockchain is a public ledger. Your writing becomes part of the permanent public record.
This is a feature, not a bug. Public means verifiable. Public means permanent. Public means no one can claim it was different.
If you need private documents, Bitcoin Writer isn't the right tool. Use encryption, use private servers, use whatever fits your needs. But if you want something public and permanent â€” a statement, a record, a proof â€” then public is exactly what you want.
