What follows is a full, end-to-end description of $PATH, written as if it were the spec youâ€™d hand to an incubator, a newsroom, or an engineer and say: this is what it is; decide if you want it.

The $PATH Protocol
Early Access Pricing for Information

1. What $PATH Is
$PATH is a pricing and distribution protocol for information on the web.

It turns a URL path into a market.

A regular path tells a browser where a resource lives.
A $PATH tells the network:

this resource has a price

the price changes as demand changes

early buyers pay more

later buyers pay less

access settles immediately

Nothing else is assumed.

No ideology.
No permanence requirement.
No promise of profit.

Just a mechanism for capturing value before information spreads.

2. The Problem $PATH Solves
Information has two contradictory properties:

Early access is scarce

Distribution is inevitable

Today, the web only monetises the second.

Creators publish â†’ platforms distribute â†’ platforms monetise scale.
Creators get exposure, not leverage.

The only moment creators actually have leverage is before distribution.

That moment currently has no native economic primitive.

$PATH exists to price that moment.

3. How a $PATH Is Defined
A $PATH is created by prefixing a URL segment with $.

/blog/my-post          â† free path
/$blog/$my-post        â† priced path
Each $ segment represents an independent market.

Example:

$b0ase.com                 â† site access
$b0ase.com/$blog           â† section access
$b0ase.com/$blog/$post     â† content access
Each segment may have:

a base price

a decay curve

an issuer share

The total price is the sum of the segments.

This allows pricing at multiple granularities without subscriptions or bundles.

4. The Pricing Model
4.1 Base Price
The creator sets an initial price.

This is the price of first access.

For a witness video:

$10,000 might be reasonable

For a research memo:

$50 might be reasonable

For a blog post:

5 sats might be reasonable

There is no â€œcorrectâ€ price.
The market decides whether the creator was right.

4.2 Price Decay
Prices fall as supply increases.

Default curve: square-root decay.

Buyer #1 pays full price

Buyer #100 pays ~10%

Buyer #10,000 pays ~1%

This is deliberate.

High prices discourage distribution.
Falling prices encourage it.

The curve is the distribution strategy.

No algorithms.
No promotion.
No platform intervention.

4.3 Why Early Buyers Still Buy
Early buyers pay more, but they get:

immediate access

time advantage

resale / serving optionality

This is not a promise of profit.

It is a position, not an entitlement.

Most buyers will not make money.
Some will.
That is expected.

5. Payment & Access (HTTP 402)
$PATH uses HTTP 402 Payment Required.

Flow:

Client requests $PATH

Server responds with 402 + price terms

Client decides: pay or skip

Payment settles instantly

Content is delivered

This works best for:

AI agents

crawlers

research systems

private networks

Humans arrive later, once prices have decayed.

6. Serving & Redistribution
$PATH does not enforce behaviour.

After purchase:

some buyers will serve

some will cache

some will repackage

some will copy and repost

The protocol does not care.

Why?

Because the creatorâ€™s leverage was upfront.

Once information is loose:

copying is inevitable

enforcement is pointless

ideology breaks

$PATH monetises the window before inevitability.

7. Storage & Permanence
$PATH does not require permanent storage.

It only requires:

settlement of access

verifiable issuance

auditable pricing

Whether content:

persists

disappears

is archived

is forgotten

is an economic decision.

Some content is worth keeping forever.
Most isnâ€™t.

$PATH is agnostic.

8. What $PATH Is Not
Not an NFT

Not a subscription

Not a paywall

Not DRM

Not a moral system

Not a guarantee of income

It does not prevent copying.
It does not enforce fairness.
It does not promise wealth.

It only prices when access happens.

9. Who Pays (Reality)
In practice, first buyers are usually:

news organisations

research firms

AI agents

analysts

aggregators

These actors:

have budgets

value speed

donâ€™t experience micropayment friction

End users rarely see the transaction.

They see the result.

This is intentional.

10. Why This Works in Private Networks First
$PATH is strongest where:

identity is known

budgets exist

discovery is scoped

demand is intentional

Examples:

incubators

research labs

legal networks

journalism collectives

internal knowledge systems

Public web adoption is optional, not required.

11. Economic Summary
Creators price early access

Early buyers absorb risk

Prices fall automatically

Distribution accelerates

Platforms can repackage freely

Permanence is optional

Value is captured before virality

No ideology required.

12. The Core Claim (Nothing More)
$PATH gives information a way to get paid once, at the moment it is most valuable, without trying to control what happens after.

Thatâ€™s the whole thing.

